<HEADLINE>
<P>
IF WE REALLY WANT TO COME UP AS WINNERS, WE'D BEGIN TO CURB OUR LOTTERY FEVER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NEAL R. PEIRCE, Neal R. Peirce is a Washington writer on state and local 
government policy. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With the national media feeding the frenzy, people flew in from all over 
America to gamble on Pennsylvania's $115-million record-setting jackpot, the 
biggest since Illinois set its $69-million record 12 days earlier. 
</P>
<P>
"I'll be rich tomorrow," a postal worker tells a reporter after standing in 
line three hours to buy her tickets. 
</P>
<P>
Whatever the long, snaking queues and 500 ticket-per-second sales have to say 
about our national condition, it isn't good. Lotteries, once the peculiar 
blight of impoverished Third World countries, are mushrooming across 28 states 
-- even as the U.S. savings rate sinks to the lowest in the industrialized 
world. 
</P>
<P>
Why this lottery craze, now? Sheer materialism, fed by media hype? Lack of 
individual or national purpose? Erosion of the work ethic? There's no one 
answer. But players for the Pennsylvania jackpot did repeatedly tell 
interviewers they'd use the loot, if they won, for a house. Until the 1970s, 
the American dream -- and practice -- was to work hard, save weekly, then make 
the down payment on your own home. Now peoples' hopes get boiled down to 
million-to-one odds. Perhaps our national standard of living is plummeting 
faster than we realize. 
</P>
<P>
States used to treat gambling as a faintly tainted activity, at best. No 
longer. Now it's the states' silver bullet, a substitute for politically 
dangerous taxes. States are hooked, like their gambling citizens. A decade ago, 
less than $2 billion worth of lottery tickets were sold nationwide; states 
netted $730 million. But last year, Americans bought more than $15 billion 
worth of lottery tickets. Net revenue soared to $5.8 billion. New Jersey and 
California may soon net $1 billion each. 
</P>
<P>
So the money is getting deadly serious. And the lottery rash keeps spreading. A 
last bastion, the South, is now crumbling. Florida and Virginia recently 
succumbed; Louisiana and Georgia are teetering. 
</P>
<P>
Lotteries have become a huge, regressive, debilitating tax -- especially on 
lower-income people. Statewide sales of more than $100 per adult per year are 
commonplace, meaning that hundreds of thousands of individuals are spending 
more than $1,000 on the tickets. A study in New Jersey found that more than 
one-third of families that live in poverty at under $10,000 a year spend 
one-fifth of their income on lotteries. 
</P>
<P>
If lotteries were a harmless form of entertainment, who could oppose them? But 
they can become an addiction. "We're building a nation of gamblers," says 
Arnold Wexler, executive director of New Jersey's Council on Compulsive 
Gambling. Buying a state lottery ticket is many people's first brush with 
gambling -- a potentially "devastating illness that takes away your whole 
life," says Wexler, a compulsive gambler who kicked the habit 21 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
Lottery-driven gambling might indeed become the national addiction of the '90s, 
as serious as alcohol, drug abuse and cigarette smoking. 
</P>
<P>
So what do we do other than turn the wheel of history back to 1964 when New 
Hampshire unleashed the first state lottery of the 20th Century? 
</P>
<P>
A huge scandal, like the corruption that killed Louisiana's lottery in 1894, 
might dampen, even kill off today's craze. Short of that, seven stopgap steps 
come to mind: 
</P>
<P>
First, curb the outrageous $400-million-a-year lottery ad campaigns that states 
finance and countenance. A billboard in a Chicago ghetto reads: "This could be 
your ticket out." A New York TV ad, cited by the Citizens League in Minnesota, 
showed a mother telling her daughter that she should stop striving for a 
scholarship because Mom's buying lottery tickets. An Illinois ad showed a man 
scoffing at people investing in savings bonds, saying that he's investing in 
the lottery and that it's the only way he'll be a millionaire. 
</P>
<P>
Lottery ads should be banned. The media hypes the games enough -- for free. 
Short of that, state-sponsored ads should conform to some minimal standards of 
truth telling, noting the odds against winning, and warning that gambling can 
become addictive. 
</P>
<P>
Second, the states ought to print warnings about compulsive gambling directly 
on the tickets (as we now insist for cigarette packaging). 
</P>
<P>
Third, state lotteries should funnel more cash into treatment programs for the 
addicts their own public gambling help create. Reserving a minimal 1% of New 
Jersey's lottery and casino revenues, for example, would create a $8 
million-a-year treatment fund, compared to the measly $275,000 the state spends 
now. 
</P>
<P>
Fourth, cap the size of jackpots. They have a spiraling effect, drawing more 
and more people, siphoning off more and more cash needed for family budgets and 
education and savings. 
</P>
<P>
Fifth, limit the spread of lottery outlets. An example of today's abuse: 
California has started putting mini-lottery terminals in checkout lines of some 
supermarkets. 
</P>
<P>
Sixth, stop pretending that education, old folks' programs or state 
economic-development programs really benefit from lottery sales. Lottery 
funding just supplants other necessary state appropriations. It encourages 
people to think that in government, as in gambling itself, you can get what you 
want for nothing. 
</P>
<P>
Final suggestion: If you hear anyone seriously propose a national lottery, tell 
him the facts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA050989-0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 54444 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 9, 1989, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 7; Column 1; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
