<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST HOLLYWOOD TO STUDY FORMATION OF POLICE DEPT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RON RUSSELL, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a surprise move, the West Hollywood City Council has authorized a study to 
determine how much it would cost to establish its own police department. 
</P>
<P>
City Manager Paul Brotzman cautioned that the study by the city's 
administrative staff does not mean that West Hollywood is interested in forming 
its own police force. 
</P>
<P>
Instead, he and other officials said they expect the study to show that West 
Hollywood's arrangement with the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department for 
law enforcement protection is a bargain. 
</P>
<P>
"It's basically a documentation exercise," Brotzman said. "It shouldn't be 
interpreted by the Sheriff's Department or anyone else as a first step in 
establishing a municipal police force." 
</P>
<P>
Some gay activists, who have been critical of the Sheriff's Department and have 
demanded that the city explore the possibility of establishing its own force, 
were skeptical. 
</P>
<P>
"Instead of a feasibility study, it sounds more like a mechanism to justify a 
decision that's already been made," said Jean Conger, executive director of 
Southern California Women for Understanding, a lesbian rights group. 
</P>
<P>
The Sheriff's Department provides service to West Hollywood, where an estimated 
35% of the 37,000 residents are gay, under an $8.5-million annual contract that 
expires next year. About 120 deputies are assigned to the city. 
</P>
<P>
Although West Hollywood officials have praised the department for its 
crime-fighting abilities, gays have frequently complained of being harassed by 
deputies. Gay rights activists have also complained that there are no 
acknowledged gays among the department's 7,000 deputies. 
</P>
<P>
About 50 gay activists have endorsed a petition circulated by City Councilman 
Steve Schulte demanding that the department recruit openly gay men and women. 
</P>
<P>
The petition dismisses as inadequate a February agreement between West 
Hollywood and the Sheriff's Department aimed at recruiting gays as deputies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
